  footnotes: []
english:
  title: In Response to the Rhymes of Yuesongjing Pavilion at Pinghai
  author: Song In
  language: eng
  text: |-
    This land borders on Penglai and Fangzhang—sacred peaks of legend.
    How many seasons have passed since the immortal of Yuesongjing departed?
    Searching for wonders through these lands, my journey rushes onward,
    And I lament how brief my leave has been, how hard it is to linger.
    Old friends—I do not meet them, only their faces linger in memory.
    Though this fine temple brings joy, what can brighten a weary heart?
    Tomorrow at dawn I journey toward the hot springs,
    But who will follow this solitary wanderer, bottle in hand, through the empty dark?
  footnotes:
    - Penglai and Fangzhang are legendary islands of immortals in classical Chinese cosmology, suggesting the sacred nature of the landscape.
    - Yuesongjing (月松亭) refers to the Pavilion of the Moon and Pine, a place of spiritual significance.
    - The poem's final image of seeking a companion for wine conveys both loneliness and the desire for connection in travel.
